[normal]1.
[normal]              
[normal]How has antimicrobial resistance developed in the past decade?
[normal]Bacteria
[normal]Notable successes have included the halt, and subsequent reversal, of the rise in 
[normal]bacteraemias
[normal] caused by 
[normal]meticillin
[normal]-resistant 
[normal]Staphylococcus 
[normal]aureus
[normal] (MRSA) and the decline in infections caused by 
[normal]resistant 
[normal]pneumococci
[normal] strains of serotypes covered by available vaccines
[normal]. However, these declines have been offset by a significant rise in infections caused by increasingly resistant Gram-negative bacteria, for example 
[normal]carbapenem
[normal]-resistant 
[normal]Enterobacteriaceae
[normal]. Such resistant strains have come to epitomize the resistance threat, with few licensed antibiotics offering effective treatment options.
[normal]Viruses 
[normal]Resistance to one of the two licensed classes of influenza antiviral drug (
[normal]adamantanes
[normal]) has become widespread since 2003. All currently circulating strains are adamantine-resistant, including the A(H7N9) virus currently causing outbreaks in China. This leaves two neuraminidase inhibitors as the only effective licensed anti-influenza drugs. However, resistance to 
[normal]Tamiflu
[normal] emerged in one subtype of influenza virus in 2007-8, and within a year had become the first incidence of global neuraminidase inhibitor resistance. There are fears that resistance could develop and spread as rapidly in the pandemic strain; a surprising number of patients infected in China with the avian A(H7N9) virus have developed 
[normal]Tamiflu
[normal]-resistant virus, leading to concerns that resistance may develop more readily in this strain. Neuraminidase resistance in highly pathogenic potential pandemic strains is a challenge for pandemic planning, antiviral stockpiling and outbreak management.
[normal]Fungi 
[normal]There is evidence of both emerging and innate resistance to different groups of antifungal drugs amongst common yeast isolates. In recent years multidrug-resistant isolates have emerged, although numbers are still quite low. 
[normal]In countries such as the Netherlands and surrounding areas there is concern about the spread of one or more 
[normal]azole
[normal]-resistant 
[normal]clades
[normal] of
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]the mould 
[normal]Aspergillus
[normal] 
[normal]fumigatus
[normal], which is responsible for about 80% of invasive mould infections. The resistance appears to be due to mutations, which were probably selected by the use of agricultural azoles, and could severely limit the use of the first-line agent 
[normal]voriconazole
[normal] as well as other 
[normal]azole
[normal] drugs
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]in treatment of infections due to this mould. Some other mould species that cause deep infections have only limited susceptibility to current agents, while others are resistant to all currently available agents.
[normal]Development of resistance during long-term therapy is a problem for both refractory yeast and chronic 
[normal]Aspergillus
[normal] infections.
[normal]Parasites/Malaria
[normal]There has been further spread of drug resistant 
[normal]Plasmodium 
[normal]falciparum
[normal] and now 
[normal]P. 
[normal]vivax
[normal] malaria; drug-resistant 
[normal]Fasciola
[normal] hepatica
[normal] has been detected in UK livestock; 
[normal]Leishmania
[normal] 
[normal]donovani
[normal] showing 
[normal]significant resistance to 
[normal]antimonial
[normal] drugs has become established in India; and cases of 
[normal]Giardia
[normal] infection clinically resistant to the 
[normal]nitroimidazoles
[normal] (e.g. 
[normal]metronidazole
[normal]) are increasingly recognised.
