[normal]What are the gaps in our knowledge about antimicrobial resistance?
[normal]Bacteria
[normal]One major uncertainty, despite the agreed need for antimicrobial stewardship to prevent and slow resistance, is exactly what good stewardship looks like. There is a tendency in the UK to equate stewardship with simply minimising use of antibiotics such as 
[normal]cephalosporins
[normal] and 
[normal]fluoroquinolones
[normal]. Consequently, there have been major increases in the use of a very narrow range of alternative antibiotics, especially an antibiotic called 
[normal]piperacillin-tazobactam
[normal]. This can be equated to 'squeezing the balloon' by potentially creating a resistance problem elsewhere. Rather than ‘swinging the pendulum’ away from use of what might be the most effective antibiotic for the patient (e.g. use of 
[normal]cephalosporins
[normal]), improving knowledge about appropriate prescribing is required.
[normal]Viruses
[normal]Influenza: 
[normal]Hepatitis C Virus (HCV):
[normal]Human Immunodeficiency Virus (HIV):
[normal]Fungi
[normal]Parasites/Malaria
[normal]a)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Molecular determinants of slow parasite clearance after 
[normal]artemisinin
[normal] treatment in SE Asia, considered by some to be the early signs of emergence of true resistance, are still unknown although some candidates have been identified but not yet validated; thus markers may be available for surveillance in the UK within 12 months 
[normal]b)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The Malaria Reference Laboratory is currently validating new markers associated with ACT treatment failure in the context of African 
[normal]Plasmodium 
[normal]falciparum
[normal] malaria - this appears to be a different phenomenon.
[normal]c)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Almost all UK cases of 
[normal]falciparum
[normal] malaria are of African origin, which should inform our surveillance and treatment policy for imported malaria cases. The role of asymptomatic cases in endemic countries as reservoirs of drug-insensitive parasites is becoming an important topic but needs more concerted attention to inform our practice in the UK.
[normal]d)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Treatment failure with the current best practice-preferred combination regimen (
[normal]artemether-lumefantrine
[normal]) is extremely rare – we have had only one well-documented case since this regimen entered widespread use, and this responded to rescue treatment (
[normal]atovaquone-proguanil
[normal]).
[normal]e)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The European Medicines Authority (EMA) has recently licensed two further 
[normal]artemisinin
[normal]-based 
[normal]antimalarial
[normal] combinations (
[normal]dihydroartemisinin-piperaquine
[normal]; 
[normal]artesunate-pyronaridine
[normal]) and these are likely to be very effective second-line regimens in rare cases of 
[normal]artemether-lumefantrine
[normal] failure. 
[normal]f)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]UK malaria drugs policy and surveillance for 
[normal]antimalarial
[normal] resistance must maintain cross-talk between thorough monitoring of our imported malaria burden, and the most recent data from the field in the endemic areas from which the bulk of our cases originate – Nigeria, Ghana, Sierra Leone and other 
[normal]anglophone
[normal] sub-Saharan nations. 
