[normal]Is there sufficient research and investment into new antibiotics or other treatments and methods to ensure continued protection against infection? If not, how could this be rectified?
[normal]Bacteria
[normal]With a limited scope for public funding, addressing the critical need to increase the range of alternative antibiotics is a huge challenge in the work to combat rises in infections caused by resistant bacteria. There is a need to identify why the costs of research are so high and seek to reduce them. An alternative approach to public funding would be to work to attract private investment. The GAIN Act in the US is a useful model, effectively extending patent life. More generally, barriers to entry could be reduced. High costs mean that that only a few large companies can run Phase III trials. In relation to other treatments and methods, there is a need for stronger research programmes into non-antibiotic treatments for infection such as 
[normal]biologicals
[normal], monoclonal antibodies, and new vehicles for rapid vaccine development. 
[normal]Viruses
[normal]Influenza: There are several 
[normal]antivirals
[normal] in phase 2 and 3 clinical trials, both influenza-specific or more broadly acting, largely funded by industry or in some cases US governmental departments. Further drugs are 
[normal]licenced
[normal] in other countries (Japan, Korea), but not widely available elsewhere. Strategies to make industry investment in alternative target 
[normal]antivirals
[normal] may be worthwhile.  Increase repertoire of drugs available for treatment of severe influenza. 
[normal]HCV: Research and investment on new treatments (DAAs targeting different viral-specific functions) is increasing and the number of anti-HCV agents is expected to rival those available for HIV in the next few years.
[normal]HIV: There has been a decline in research and investment because there are a lot of anti-
[normal]retrovirals
[normal] on the market (including cheaper generic forms).  However, unlike anti-HCV agents, anti-
[normal]retrovirals
[normal] do 
[normal]not eradicate HIV from the body. Therefore, infected individuals have to remain on therapy for life at a cost of ~£16,000 per year. Thus, more research funding is required for eradication or transmission prevention strategies.
[normal]Fungi 
[normal]There are currently no antifungal agents with novel mechanisms of action in the development pipeline. There is also a need for development of better diagnostic tests to reduce the unnecessary use of empirical therapy.
[normal]Parasites/Malaria
[normal]The main problem with parasitic diseases of humans is reliance on only one drug or reliance on old, toxic agents.  In the case of tropical parasites this is very largely due to lack of investment in new drug research and development.
[normal]The following parasites give rise to particular concern:
[normal]Malaria
[normal]One approach to support this could be 
[normal]DfID
[normal] and RCUK specific calls for project proposals in the twin areas of malaria resistance monitoring in endemic areas AND drug discovery projects at all phases of the pipeline. 
[normal]Trichomonas
[normal] 
[normal]vaginalis
[normal]: 
[normal]Nitroimidazoles
[normal] (
[normal]metronidazole
[normal] or 
[normal]tinidazole
[normal]) are the only oral agents available to treat this very common condition. 
[normal]Fasciola
[normal] hepatica: 
[normal]Triclabendazole
[normal]-resistant 
[normal]Fasciola
[normal] is found in UK livestock and is present globally.  We have no second line drug for use in humans if 
[normal]triclabendazole
[normal] fails.
[normal]Schistosomiasis
[normal]; 
[normal]Praziquantel
[normal] is the only drug available for the treatment of human 
[normal]schistosomiasis
[normal].
[normal]Trypanosoma
[normal] 
[normal]cruzi
[normal]:
[normal] 
[normal]The only drugs available, 
[normal]benznidazole
[normal] and 
[normal]nifurtimox
[normal], are very toxic (significant side-effects in 50% of cases).
[normal]Trypanosoma
[normal] 
[normal]brucei
[normal] spp.:
[normal] 
[normal]Some drugs are toxic and very old. 
[normal]Eg
[normal] 
[normal]melarsoprol
[normal], an arsenical compound (sic), is still in use.
[normal]Hydatid
[normal] disease:
[normal] 
[normal]Benzimidazoles
[normal] (
[normal]albendazole
[normal], with the less-effective 
[normal]mebendazole
[normal] as alternative) are the mainstay of medical treatment. There is no good alternative to these agents. 
[normal]Cryptosporidium:
[normal] 
[normal]There is only one effective drug (
[normal]nitazoxanide
[normal]).
